      <div class="article-teaser">
        <p>A small number of vehicles are entitled to an exemption from the Low Emission Zone (LEZ).</p>
        
      </div>
    
    
      <p>These are:</p>

<ul>
	<li>Specialist vehicles designed and built for mainly off-road use, but which may use the road for limited purposes (including agricultural and forestry tractors, mowing machines, agricultural and farm machinery and equipment, mobile cranes and road and building construction machinery)</li>
	<li>Vehicles built before 1 January 1973</li>
	<li>Vehicles with&nbsp;historic tax class</li>
	<li>Vehicles operated by the Ministry of Defence</li>
</ul>

<p>If your vehicle meets any of the above criteria and is registered in the UK, it is automatically exempt and you don't<strong>&nbsp;</strong>need to register with us. However, you may not qualify for an <a href="https://tfl.gov.uk/modes/driving/ultra-low-emission-zone/discounts-and-exemptions">exemption from the ULEZ charge</a>.</p>

<p>If your vehicle meets any of the above criteria but is registered outside the UK, you are also exempt, but <strong>will </strong>need to <a href="/modes/driving/low-emission-zone/find-out-if-you-need-to-register/how-to-register">register with us</a>.</p>

<p><strong>All of these vehicles are also exempt from the <a href="https://tfl.gov.uk/modes/driving/low-emission-zone/changes-to-the-lez">tougher LEZ emissions standards</a> being implemented from 26 October 2020.</strong></p>
      
           
      
